missingvalue=False
for feature in Cardf.columns:
     #check for NaN values 
    if(Cardf[feature].isnull().sum()!=0 or Cardf[feature].isna().sum()!=0 ):
        print("Data missing in column", feature)
        #impute
        impute = SimpleImputer(missing_values = np.nan, strategy = 'mean', verbose = 1)
        Cardf[feature] =impute.fit_transform(Cardf[feature] )
        missingvalue= True

    print("No Missing Values")

#H. Check for unexpected values in all the features and datapoints with such values. 
unexpected_values = ["n/a", "na", "--", " ","?","-","@","#","n-a"]
unexpected=False
for feature in Cardf.columns: 
    #check for unexpected values like special characters.     
    if (not Cardf[Cardf[feature].isin(unexpected_values)].empty):  
        print("Unexpected value found in",feature,"column in the indices ", Cardf[Cardf[feature].isin(unexpected_values)].index)
        #changing unexpected values to NaN
        Cardf[feature].replace(unexpected_values,np.nan, inplace=True) 
         #impute
        Cardf[feature].fillna( round(Cardf[feature].mean()), inplace=True)
        print("Imputed unexpected value in column",feature,"with",round(Cardf[feature].mean()))
        unexpected = True
           
        
if(not unexpected):
     print("No unexpected values")

3. Clustering:¶

In [16]:
#A. Apply K-Means clustering for 2 to 10 clusters.
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
Cardfnumerical=Cardf.iloc[:,1:9]
Cardfscaled=Cardfnumerical.apply(zscore)
clusters=range(2,11)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(Cardfscaled)
    prediction=model.predict(Cardfscaled)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(Cardfscaled, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / Cardfscaled.shape[0])
In [17]:
#B. Plot a visual and find elbow point.
plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
plt.show()

k=5 and k=3 are possible elbow point , will find optimal k value after calculating wss and silhoutee

PART-B¶

DOMAIN: Automobile

• CONTEXT: The purpose is to classify a given silhouette as one of three types of vehicle, using a set of features extracted from the silhouette. The vehicle may be viewed from one of many different angles.

• DATA DESCRIPTION: The data contains features extracted from the silhouette of vehicles in different angles. Four "Corgie" model vehicles were used for the experiment: a double decker bus, Cheverolet van, Saab 9000 and an Opel Manta 400 cars. This particular combination of vehicles was chosen with the expectation that the bus, van and either one of the cars would be readily distinguishable, but it would be more difficult to distinguish between the cars. • All the features are numeric i.e. geometric features extracted from the silhouette.

• PROJECT OBJECTIVE: Apply dimensionality reduction technique – PCA and train a model and compare relative results

5. Data Understanding & Cleaning:¶

A. Explain pre-requisite/assumptions of PCA.¶

  1. Feature must be correlated to each other
  2. Data should be normalized
  3. Principal component with high variance have given importance and PC with lower variance are considered as noise.
  4. increased outliers will degrade the performance

B. Explain advantages and limitations of PCA.¶

Advantages of PCA:

  1. It reduces the dimensions of the data thereby reduce the complexity of the model
  2. Improve the performance with decreased computational time
  3. Also helps in preventing the model from overfitting
  4. Lesser dimension makes visualization easier.
  5. Removes multi-collinearity to improve ML model performance

Disadvantages of PCA-

  1. Information loss.
  2. Data normalization must be needed before applying PCA
  3. Independent variables are becoming less interpretable
In [ ]:
